Q6a Establish a baseline and define the problems and risks, including both cyber and physical. #IICSecurity
A6 Begin with basic controls like authentication & standardizing network protocols. And limit unnecessary data collection. #IICSecurity
A6 First, as we mentioned before, start small. And educate yourself and your team. #IICSecurity
A5 @IIConsortium emphasis on encryption of data in transit is critical. #IICSecurity
A5 @IIConsortium dynamic, attribute based access control. We can authenticate devices based on where they are, etc. #IICSecurity
Q4 @IIConsortium we're curious: does the group have any thoughts on the NIST Draft Framework on Cyber-Physical Systems? #IICSecurity
RT @IIConsortium: Looks like we are all in agreement thus far that, right now, open #iiot #security standards are the way to go #IICSecurity
A4 Open standards, but we're really a long way away from where we need to be. Education is essential. #IICSecurity
A3 Yes, Absolutely. The key is risk management. #IICSecurity
A2 @SmartIndustryUS @BeldenInc agreed. Starting small is key.  #IICSecurity
A2 @IIConsortium all points raised are good, but good design and controls can address both intentional and unintentional threats.
A1 @IIConsortium in general, security is lacking. But we've seen some success with network segmentation. #IICSecurity
Q1 @IIConsortium check out the OWASP Top Ten for some helpful starting points #IICSecurity : https://t.co/3zrb3CifHF
